When you add an event listener, it captures the current state of the index. However, by the time the event is triggered, the index might have been updated. 

To avoid this, you can use an arrow function to capture the current index at the time of adding the event listener. Here's an example:

```javascript
// Assuming you have an array of stars
stars.forEach((star, index) => {
  star.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log(index);
  });
});
```

In this example, the `index` variable is captured at the time of adding the event listener, so it will always log the correct index when the event is triggered.

Alternatively, you can use a closure to achieve the same result:

```javascript
stars.forEach((star, index) => {
  const currentIndex = index;
  star.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log(currentIndex);
  });
});
```

However, using an arrow function is generally more concise and easier to read.

